And the whole entire code contained only two hundred and seven canons, following one another in an exact order, to the end that the number of them might neither be augmented nor diminished. And thus it continued till Dionysius Exiguus his timei, who, being an abbot of Rome, translated that code out of Greek into Latin after another manner than it had been in use be- fore, and made many alterations in it. For he retrenched divers of the ancient canonsk, which seemed to be most dis- advantageous to the popes, and added divers othersl that the universal Church did not acknowledge: yet in all his col- lection was there never any decretal epistle added.
